{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":882,"text":"Just after Christmas last year,"},{"time":3482,"text":"132 kids in California got the measles"},{"time":7320,"text":"by either visiting Disneyland"},{"time":9333,"text":"or being exposed to someone\nwho'd been there."},{"time":12282,"text":"The virus then hopped the Canadian border,"},{"time":15486,"text":"infecting more than\n100 children in Quebec."},{"time":18922,"text":"One of the tragic things\nabout this outbreak"},{"time":21871,"text":"is that measles, which can be fatal\nto a child with a weakened immune system,"},{"time":27490,"text":"is one of the most easily\npreventable diseases in the world."},{"time":31275,"text":"An effective vaccine against it"},{"time":33272,"text":"has been available for more\nthan half a century,"},{"time":36638,"text":"but many of the kids involved\nin the Disneyland outbreak"},{"time":39912,"text":"had not been vaccinated"},{"time":41886,"text":"because their parents were afraid"},{"time":44138,"text":"of something allegedly even worse:"},{"time":47157,"text":"autism."}]},{"cues":[{"time":48875,"text":"But wait -- wasn't the paper\nthat sparked the controversy"},{"time":52658,"text":"about autism and vaccines"},{"time":54981,"text":"debunked, retracted,"},{"time":56978,"text":"and branded a deliberate fraud"},{"time":59450,"text":"by the British Medical Journal?"},{"time":61158,"text":"Don't most science-savvy people"},{"time":63201,"text":"know that the theory\nthat vaccines cause autism is B.S.?"},{"time":67520,"text":"I think most of you do,"},{"time":69377,"text":"but millions of parents worldwide"},{"time":71955,"text":"continue to fear that vaccines\nput their kids at risk for autism."}]},{"cues":[{"time":76923,"text":"Why?"},{"time":78827,"text":"Here's why."},{"time":80290,"text":"This is a graph of autism\nprevalence estimates rising over time."},{"time":85375,"text":"For most of the 20th century,"},{"time":87488,"text":"autism was considered\nan incredibly rare condition."},{"time":91180,"text":"The few psychologists and pediatricians\nwho'd even heard of it"},{"time":94500,"text":"figured they would get through\ntheir entire careers"},{"time":97217,"text":"without seeing a single case."},{"time":100364,"text":"For decades, the prevalence estimates\nremained stable"},{"time":103602,"text":"at just three or four children in 10,000."},{"time":106853,"text":"But then, in the 1990s,"},{"time":108919,"text":"the numbers started to skyrocket."},{"time":111380,"text":"Fundraising organizations\nlike Autism Speaks"},{"time":114608,"text":"routinely refer to autism as an epidemic,"},{"time":117696,"text":"as if you could catch it\nfrom another kid at Disneyland."}]},{"cues":[{"time":121365,"text":"So what's going on?"},{"time":122967,"text":"If it isn't vaccines, what is it?"},{"time":126194,"text":"If you ask the folks down at\nthe Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta"},{"time":130165,"text":"what's going on,"},{"time":131860,"text":"they tend to rely on phrases like\n\"broadened diagnostic criteria\""},{"time":136370,"text":"and \"better case finding\""},{"time":138134,"text":"to explain these rising numbers."},{"time":140711,"text":"But that kind of language"},{"time":142731,"text":"doesn't do much to allay\nthe fears of a young mother"},{"time":145680,"text":"who is searching her\ntwo-year-old's face for eye contact."},{"time":150324,"text":"If the diagnostic criteria\nhad to be broadened,"},{"time":153319,"text":"why were they so narrow\nin the first place?"},{"time":156152,"text":"Why were cases of autism\nso hard to find"},{"time":159147,"text":"before the 1990s?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":161437,"text":"Five years ago, I decided to try\nto uncover the answers to these questions."},{"time":167172,"text":"I learned that what happened"},{"time":169216,"text":"has less to do with the slow and cautious\nprogress of science"},{"time":173116,"text":"than it does with the seductive\npower of storytelling."},{"time":176544,"text":"For most of the 20th century,"},{"time":178750,"text":"clinicians told one story"},{"time":181211,"text":"about what autism is\nand how it was discovered,"},{"time":184763,"text":"but that story turned out to be wrong,"},{"time":187573,"text":"and the consequences of it"},{"time":189384,"text":"are having a devastating impact\non global public health."},{"time":193285,"text":"There was a second,\nmore accurate story of autism"},{"time":196814,"text":"which had been lost and forgotten"},{"time":199430,"text":"in obscure corners\nof the clinical literature."},{"time":202410,"text":"This second story tells us everything\nabout how we got here"},{"time":206427,"text":"and where we need to go next."}]},{"cues":[{"time":209352,"text":"The first story starts with a child\npsychiatrist at Johns Hopkins Hospital"},{"time":213996,"text":"named Leo Kanner."},{"time":215946,"text":"In 1943, Kanner published a paper"},{"time":219499,"text":"describing 11 young patients\nwho seemed to inhabit private worlds,"},{"time":224212,"text":"ignoring the people around them,"},{"time":226302,"text":"even their own parents."},{"time":228462,"text":"They could amuse themselves for hours"},{"time":230737,"text":"by flapping their hands\nin front of their faces,"},{"time":233384,"text":"but they were panicked by little things"},{"time":235358,"text":"like their favorite toy\nbeing moved from its usual place"},{"time":238970,"text":"without their knowledge."},{"time":240977,"text":"Based on the patients\nwho were brought to his clinic,"},{"time":243693,"text":"Kanner speculated\nthat autism is very rare."},{"time":247269,"text":"By the 1950s, as the world's\nleading authority on the subject,"},{"time":251727,"text":"he declared that he had seen\nless than 150 true cases of his syndrome"},{"time":257300,"text":"while fielding referrals from\nas far away as South Africa."},{"time":261363,"text":"That's actually not surprising,"},{"time":263754,"text":"because Kanner's criteria\nfor diagnosing autism"},{"time":267130,"text":"were incredibly selective."},{"time":269443,"text":"For example, he discouraged giving\nthe diagnosis to children who had seizures"},{"time":274621,"text":"but now we know that epilepsy\nis very common in autism."},{"time":278382,"text":"He once bragged that he had turned\nnine out of 10 kids"},{"time":281424,"text":"referred to his office as autistic\nby other clinicians"},{"time":285255,"text":"without giving them an autism diagnosis."}]},{"cues":[{"time":288503,"text":"Kanner was a smart guy,"},{"time":290944,"text":"but a number of his theories\ndidn't pan out."},{"time":293113,"text":"He classified autism as a form\nof infantile psychosis"},{"time":296888,"text":"caused by cold and unaffectionate parents."},{"time":300858,"text":"These children, he said,"},{"time":302995,"text":"had been kept neatly\nin a refrigerator that didn't defrost."},{"time":307313,"text":"At the same time, however,"},{"time":309264,"text":"Kanner noticed that some\nof his young patients"},{"time":312189,"text":"had special abilities\nthat clustered in certain areas"},{"time":315602,"text":"like music, math and memory."},{"time":318853,"text":"One boy in his clinic"},{"time":320734,"text":"could distinguish between 18 symphonies\nbefore he turned two."},{"time":325796,"text":"When his mother put on\none of his favorite records,"},{"time":328443,"text":"he would correctly declare,\n\"Beethoven!\""},{"time":331809,"text":"But Kanner took a dim view\nof these abilities,"},{"time":334665,"text":"claiming that the kids\nwere just regurgitating things"},{"time":338242,"text":"they'd heard their pompous parents say,"},{"time":340865,"text":"desperate to earn their approval."},{"time":343465,"text":"As a result, autism became\na source of shame and stigma for families,"},{"time":348829,"text":"and two generations of autistic children"},{"time":351406,"text":"were shipped off to institutions\nfor their own good,"},{"time":354889,"text":"becoming invisible to the world at large."}]},{"cues":[{"time":358163,"text":"Amazingly, it wasn't until the 1970s"},{"time":362400,"text":"that researchers began to test\nKanner's theory that autism was rare."},{"time":367567,"text":"Lorna Wing was a cognitive\npsychologist in London"},{"time":371305,"text":"who thought that Kanner's theory\nof refrigerator parenting"},{"time":374509,"text":"were \"bloody stupid,\" as she told me."},{"time":377528,"text":"She and her husband John were warm\nand affectionate people,"},{"time":381707,"text":"and they had a profoundly\nautistic daughter named Susie."},{"time":385110,"text":"Lorna and John knew how hard it was\nto raise a child like Susie"},{"time":389822,"text":"without support services,"},{"time":391784,"text":"special education,"},{"time":393386,"text":"and the other resources that are\nout of reach without a diagnosis."},{"time":397635,"text":"To make the case\nto the National Health Service"},{"time":400259,"text":"that more resources were needed\nfor autistic children and their families,"}]},{"cues":[{"time":405507,"text":"Lorna and her colleague Judith Gould"},{"time":407643,"text":"decided to do something that should\nhave been done 30 years earlier."},{"time":412193,"text":"They undertook a study of autism\nprevalence in the general population."},{"time":417139,"text":"They pounded the pavement\nin a London suburb called Camberwell"},{"time":421435,"text":"to try to find autistic children\nin the community."},{"time":425100,"text":"What they saw made clear\nthat Kanner's model was way too narrow,"},{"time":429767,"text":"while the reality of autism\nwas much more colorful and diverse."},{"time":434663,"text":"Some kids couldn't talk at all,"},{"time":436806,"text":"while others waxed on at length\nabout their fascination with astrophysics,"},{"time":441542,"text":"dinosaurs or the genealogy of royalty."},{"time":445486,"text":"In other words, these children\ndidn't fit into nice, neat boxes,"},{"time":450176,"text":"as Judith put it,"},{"time":451871,"text":"and they saw lots of them,"},{"time":453752,"text":"way more than Kanner's monolithic model\nwould have predicted."}]},{"cues":[{"time":457537,"text":"At first, they were at a loss\nto make sense of their data."},{"time":461252,"text":"How had no one noticed\nthese children before?"},{"time":464380,"text":"But then Lorna came upon a reference\nto a paper that had been published"},{"time":467899,"text":"in German in 1944,"},{"time":470554,"text":"the year after Kanner's paper,"},{"time":472899,"text":"and then forgotten,"},{"time":474617,"text":"buried with the ashes of a terrible time"},{"time":477194,"text":"that no one wanted to remember\nor think about."},{"time":480445,"text":"Kanner knew about this competing paper,"},{"time":483115,"text":"but scrupulously avoided\nmentioning it in his own work."},{"time":487860,"text":"It had never even\nbeen translated into English,"},{"time":490322,"text":"but luckily, Lorna's husband spoke German,"},{"time":493285,"text":"and he translated it for her."}]},{"cues":[{"time":495932,"text":"The paper offered\nan alternate story of autism."},{"time":499624,"text":"Its author was a man named Hans Asperger,"},{"time":502317,"text":"who ran a combination clinic\nand residential school"},{"time":505591,"text":"in Vienna in the 1930s."},{"time":508331,"text":"Asperger's ideas about teaching children\nwith learning differences"},{"time":512302,"text":"were progressive even\nby contemporary standards."},{"time":515436,"text":"Mornings at his clinic began\nwith exercise classes set to music,"},{"time":519848,"text":"and the children put on plays\non Sunday afternoons."},{"time":523354,"text":"Instead of blaming parents\nfor causing autism,"},{"time":526349,"text":"Asperger framed it as a lifelong,\npolygenetic disability"},{"time":531202,"text":"that requires compassionate forms\nof support and accommodations"},{"time":535103,"text":"over the course of one's whole life."},{"time":538510,"text":"Rather than treating the kids\nin his clinic like patients,"},{"time":541395,"text":"Asperger called them\nhis little professors,"},{"time":544460,"text":"and enlisted their help in developing\nmethods of education"},{"time":548245,"text":"that were particularly suited to them."},{"time":550729,"text":"Crucially, Asperger viewed autism\nas a diverse continuum"},{"time":556460,"text":"that spans an astonishing range\nof giftedness and disability."},{"time":561584,"text":"He believed that autism\nand autistic traits are common"},{"time":565116,"text":"and always have been,"},{"time":566982,"text":"seeing aspects of this continuum\nin familiar archetypes from pop culture"},{"time":572276,"text":"like the socially awkward scientist"},{"time":574612,"text":"and the absent-minded professor."},{"time":577306,"text":"He went so far as to say,"},{"time":579419,"text":"it seems that for success\nin science and art,"},{"time":582646,"text":"a dash of autism is essential."}]},{"cues":[{"time":586292,"text":"Lorna and Judith realized that Kanner\nhad been as wrong about autism being rare"},{"time":591214,"text":"as he had been about parents causing it."},{"time":593907,"text":"Over the next several years,"},{"time":595951,"text":"they quietly worked with\nthe American Psychiatric Association"},{"time":599364,"text":"to broaden the criteria for diagnosis"},{"time":601964,"text":"to reflect the diversity of what\nthey called \"the autism spectrum.\""},{"time":605981,"text":"In the late '80s and early 1990s,"},{"time":608559,"text":"their changes went into effect,"},{"time":610857,"text":"swapping out Kanner's narrow model"},{"time":613226,"text":"for Asperger's broad and inclusive one."}]},{"cues":[{"time":616801,"text":"These changes weren't\nhappening in a vacuum."},{"time":619472,"text":"By coincidence, as Lorna and Judith\nworked behind the scenes"},{"time":623326,"text":"to reform the criteria,"},{"time":625160,"text":"people all over the world were seeing\nan autistic adult for the first time."},{"time":630176,"text":"Before \"Rain Man\" came out in 1988,"},{"time":633550,"text":"only a tiny, ingrown circle of experts\nknew what autism looked like,"},{"time":638209,"text":"but after Dustin Hoffman's unforgettable\nperformance as Raymond Babbitt"},{"time":642969,"text":"earned \"Rain Man\" four Academy Awards,"},{"time":646104,"text":"pediatricians, psychologists,"},{"time":648844,"text":"teachers and parents all over the world\nknew what autism looked like."}]},{"cues":[{"time":653534,"text":"Coincidentally, at the same time,"},{"time":656459,"text":"the first easy-to-use clinical tests\nfor diagnosing autism were introduced."},{"time":661939,"text":"You no longer had to have a connection\nto that tiny circle of experts"},{"time":666629,"text":"to get your child evaluated."}]},{"cues":[{"time":669207,"text":"The combination of \"Rain Man,\""},{"time":671320,"text":"the changes to the criteria,\nand the introduction of these tests"},{"time":675499,"text":"created a network effect,"},{"time":677774,"text":"a perfect storm of autism awareness."},{"time":681304,"text":"The number of diagnoses started to soar,"},{"time":684322,"text":"just as Lorna and Judith predicted,\nindeed hoped, that it would,"},{"time":689990,"text":"enabling autistic people\nand their families"},{"time":692106,"text":"to finally get the support\nand services they deserved."}]},{"cues":[{"time":695798,"text":"Then Andrew Wakefield came along"},{"time":697864,"text":"to blame the spike\nin diagnoses on vaccines,"},{"time":701719,"text":"a simple, powerful,"},{"time":703832,"text":"and seductively believable story"},{"time":706618,"text":"that was as wrong as Kanner's theory"},{"time":708986,"text":"that autism was rare."}]},{"cues":[{"time":711239,"text":"If the CDC's current estimate,"},{"time":714710,"text":"that one in 68 kids in America\nare on the spectrum, is correct,"},{"time":719133,"text":"autistics are one of the largest\nminority groups in the world."},{"time":723340,"text":"In recent years, autistic people\nhave come together on the Internet"},{"time":727167,"text":"to reject the notion that they\nare puzzles to be solved"},{"time":730812,"text":"by the next medical breakthrough,"},{"time":732995,"text":"coining the term \"neurodiversity\""},{"time":735456,"text":"to celebrate the varieties\nof human cognition."}]},{"cues":[{"time":739264,"text":"One way to understand neurodiversity"},{"time":741655,"text":"is to think in terms\nof human operating systems."},{"time":745324,"text":"Just because a P.C. is not running Windows\ndoesn't mean that it's broken."},{"time":750240,"text":"By autistic standards,\nthe normal human brain"},{"time":753869,"text":"is easily distractable,"},{"time":755889,"text":"obsessively social,"},{"time":757677,"text":"and suffers from a deficit\nof attention to detail."},{"time":760997,"text":"To be sure, autistic people\nhave a hard time"},{"time":763992,"text":"living in a world not built for them."},{"time":766268,"text":"[Seventy] years later, we're still\ncatching up to Asperger,"},{"time":770520,"text":"who believed that the \"cure\"\nfor the most disabling aspects of autism"},{"time":774603,"text":"is to be found in understanding teachers,"},{"time":777529,"text":"accommodating employers,"},{"time":779665,"text":"supportive communities,"},{"time":781522,"text":"and parents who have faith\nin their children's potential."}]},{"cues":[{"time":784866,"text":"An autistic [man]\nnamed Zosia Zaks once said,"},{"time":787908,"text":"\"We need all hands on deck\nto right the ship of humanity.\""},{"time":793211,"text":"As we sail into an uncertain future,"},{"time":795764,"text":"we need every form\nof human intelligence on the planet"},{"time":799502,"text":"working together to tackle\nthe challenges that we face as a society."},{"time":805469,"text":"We can't afford to waste a brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":807791,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":810136,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}